<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910618-0142</DOCNO><DOCID>910618-0142.</DOCID><HL>   Riverbend Reports   Loss of $4.3 Million   For Its Second Quarter</HL><DATE>06/18/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   CKE RIV</CO><MS>CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)FOOD RETAILERS AND WHOLESALERS, CONVENIENCE STORES (FDR)FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>EARNINGS (ERN)ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   SANGER, Calif. -- Riverbend International Corp., a foodproducts company, reported a loss of $4.3 million, or 74cents a share, on revenue of $13.2 million for its fiscalsecond quarter ended April 30.   Because of the loss, Riverbend is trying to restructureits credit arrangements. It is negotiating with banksregarding about $24.4 million in revolving credit that camedue during its second quarter.</LP><TEXT>   Riverbend also said it is in technical default on $34.5million of additional loans.   The company said that negotiations haven't resulted in &quot;asuccessful resolution&quot; and that if it's unable to resolve itsproblems its bankers may elect to call its loans.   In its year-ago period, Riverbend reported net income of$63,000, or one cent a share, on sales of $17.6 million.   The company blamed a continued decline in tomato pasteprices and a shortage of fresh fruit from the San JoaquinValley in California as major reasons for its poor results.   As part of its restructuring plans, Riverbend plans toactively pursue the sale of &quot;nonproductive&quot; assets. Thecompany said that on June 11, it entered an agreement to sellits California fresh-fruit business to Castle andamp; Cooke Inc.for $7.1 million plus contingent payments over the next threeyears.   Riverbend's stock fell 37.5 cents a share to close at$1.50 a share in composite trading on the American StockExchange yesterday.</TEXT></DOC>